<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="7" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1314,2023]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,372,1386,1411]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Redescription.</emphasis>
Length 
<quantity box="[478,635,1386,1411]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.35" metricValueMax="10.1" metricValueMin="8.6" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" unit="mm" value="9.35" valueMax="10.1" valueMin="8.6">8.6–10.1 mm</quantity>
, width 5.0– 
<quantity box="[781,875,1386,1411]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.1" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" unit="mm" value="6.1">6.1 mm</quantity>
. General color (
<figureCitation box="[1073,1217,1386,1411]" captionStart="FIGURE1" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1827,1849]" captionTargetBox="[157,1396,473,1746]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,445,1806]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE1. Habitus of Oides affinis Jacoby and O. andrewesi Jacoby. 1A. O. affinis, dorsal view; 1B. Same, ventral view; 1C. Same, lateral view; 1D. O. andrewesi, dorsal view; 1E. Same, ventral view; 1F. Same, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1115694/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Figs 1A–1C</figureCitation>
) yellow; antennae yellow, antennomeres V–XI dark brown; elytra with one pair of large black spots at apical 1/3; abdominal ventrites black except apex of ventrite V; apices of tibiae and tarsi darker. Antennae filiform in males (
<figureCitation box="[1325,1423,1458,1483]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1475,1497]" captionTargetBox="[177,1408,214,1437]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[162,1426,193,1457]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic characters of Oides affinis Jacoby. 2A. Antenna, male; 2B. Antenna, female; 2C. Penis, dorsal view; 2D.Penis, lateral view; 2E. Penis, ventral view; 2F. Abdominal ventrite VIII; 2G. Spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1115696/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
), antennomeres IV longest, VIII–X elongate, length ratios of antennomeres I–XI 1.0: 0.7: 0.9: 1.3: 1.0: 1.0: 0.9: 0.9: 0.9: 0.8: 1.2, length to width ratios of antennomeres I–XI 2.5: 2.0: 2.2: 3.3: 2.7: 2.6: 2.4: 2.5: 2.1: 2.1: 2.8; more slender in female (
<figureCitation box="[475,563,1566,1591]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1475,1497]" captionTargetBox="[177,1408,214,1437]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[162,1426,193,1457]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic characters of Oides affinis Jacoby. 2A. Antenna, male; 2B. Antenna, female; 2C. Penis, dorsal view; 2D.Penis, lateral view; 2E. Penis, ventral view; 2F. Abdominal ventrite VIII; 2G. Spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1115696/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
), length ratios of antennomeres I–XI 1.0: 0.6: 0.8: 1.1: 0.8: 0.8: 0.8: 0.8: 0.7: 0.7: 1.1, length to width ratios of antennomeres I–XI 3.0: 1.6: 2.8: 3.7: 2.7: 2.6: 2.6: 2.7: 2.7: 2.6: 3.8. Pronotum transverse, 1.8x wider than long, disc with reticulate microsculpture and dense, coarse punctures, basolateral angles distinct, apico-lateral angles rectangular, lateral margins straight from near base to middle, apically narrowed from middle; apical margin weakly concave. Elytra oblong, widest at middle, 1.4x longer than wide, disc without reticulate microsculpture but with dense, coarse punctures; moderately convex, epipleurae near lateral margins, located 9/10 distance between suture and lateral margins. Tarsomeres I of front and middle legs typical in males. Penis (
<figureCitation box="[311,450,1818,1843]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1475,1497]" captionTargetBox="[177,1408,214,1437]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[162,1426,193,1457]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic characters of Oides affinis Jacoby. 2A. Antenna, male; 2B. Antenna, female; 2C. Penis, dorsal view; 2D.Penis, lateral view; 2E. Penis, ventral view; 2F. Abdominal ventrite VIII; 2G. Spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1115696/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Figs 2C–2E</figureCitation>
) slender, 5.8x longer than wide; parallel-sided; bifurcate at apical 1/4, lateral process parallel, subapically narrowed, apices of lateral processes rounded and separated; tectum elongate, apex curved; with one pair of curved ridges at apical 1/4; slightly curved in lateral view, apices rounded; ventral surface deep and broad notch from apex to apical 2/5; endophallic sac without sclerites. Apical margin of abdominal ventrite V in female truncate. Gonocoxae reduced. Ventrite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[776,866,1962,1987]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1475,1497]" captionTargetBox="[177,1408,214,1437]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[162,1426,193,1457]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic characters of Oides affinis Jacoby. 2A. Antenna, male; 2B. Antenna, female; 2C. Penis, dorsal view; 2D.Penis, lateral view; 2E. Penis, ventral view; 2F. Abdominal ventrite VIII; 2G. Spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1115696/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Fig. 2F</figureCitation>
) transverse, apical margin broadly rounded but medially depressed, with dense, long setae along apical margin; spiculum short. Receptacle of spermatheca (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1475,1497]" captionTargetBox="[177,1408,214,1437]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[162,1426,193,1457]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic characters of Oides affinis Jacoby. 2A. Antenna, male; 2B. Antenna, female; 2C. Penis, dorsal view; 2D.Penis, lateral view; 2E. Penis, ventral view; 2F. Abdominal ventrite VIII; 2G. Spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1115696/files/figure.png" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="7" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
Fig. 
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,392]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">2G) as wide as pump, connected to pump; pump strongly curved; proximal spermathecal duct membranous, slender and short, sclerotized area at apex with scale-like depression.</paragraph>
</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,392]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1437,1567,2024]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,223,248]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Members of this species are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fabricius)" authorityName="Fabricius" box="[879,1140,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palleata">
<emphasis box="[879,1008,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. palleata</emphasis>
(Fabricius)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Jacoby" authorityName="Jacoby" box="[1198,1436,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andrewesi">
<emphasis box="[1198,1349,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. andrewesi</emphasis>
Jacoby
</taxonomicName>
with reddish elytra and one pair of large black spots at apical 1/3, but they differ in possessing shining elytra and their relatively smaller size. The aedeagi of adult males of 
<taxonomicName box="[854,963,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis box="[854,963,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName box="[1250,1402,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andrewesi">
<emphasis box="[1250,1402,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. andrewesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in possessing relatively shorter lateral processes but differ in possessing a well sclerotized tectum (reduced in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andrewesi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. andrewesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and abruptly narrowed bases of lateral processes (gradually anrrowed bases in 
<taxonomicName box="[1162,1310,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Oides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="andrewesi">
<emphasis box="[1162,1310,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. andrewesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) 
